Defines the `ctx-scan` CLI surface (arg parsing via `clap`) and the top-level entry points the binary calls into after parsing: `list_targets`, `check`, `stop_hook`, and `dispatch`. Doesn't perform scanning itself — delegates to `crate::runner` (`check_run`, `scan_run`, `update_run`) and `crate::walker::walk_dir`; this file is glue between argv and those.

`Cli`/`Mode` encode mutually-exclusive run modes via clap's `conflicts_with`/`conflicts_with_all`: `--stop-hook` conflicts with `--dry-run`, `--check`, `--update`; `--dry-run` and `--check` each conflict with `--update`. Default (no mode flags) is a full scan. `--approve` is a cost/blast-radius gate consumed downstream in `runner.rs` (`MAX_TARGETS`), not enforced here.

`stop_hook` is the Claude Code Stop-hook integration: it never calls the agent (regeneration is deferred to `--update`, a session-end concern), always fails open — any error should be treated as "say nothing" by the caller — and emits `{"systemMessage": ...}` JSON only when the tree is stale (silent on a fresh tree). The message text is built by `staleness_message`, which pre-hints `--approve` in the suggested command when `changed_files.len() > ctx_summarize::runner::MAX_TARGETS`, so following the printed command never dead-ends on the gate — keep this threshold logic in sync with `runner::MAX_TARGETS`'s actual enforcement.

`dispatch<A: Agent, W: Write>(agent: &A, cli: &Cli, out: &mut W) -> Result<(), ScanError>` is the main non-hook path: routes to `update_run` (selective rebuild) or `scan_run` (full scan) based on `cli.update()`, rendering either a `Staleness` report or `ScanSummary`. All directory-taking entry points call `validate_dir`, which requires an existing directory and canonicalizes it — `ScanError::DirNotFound` otherwise.

`prompts` path is resolved against the process cwd, not the scanned `dir` — a detail callers must preserve if invoking from scripts.